{
  "answer": "In *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*, Sanskrit doctrinal terms are indeed embedded directly within Old Javanese (Kawi) sentences, untranslated, as seen in the transliteration (e.g., *bajra*, *samaya*, *maṇḍala*) and mirrored in the English translation.[^1][^2] Three clear examples:\n\n- *Vajra* (*bajra*): \"the Lord of the Three Syllables is the ultimate reality, the *vajra* [*bajra*] of body, speech, and mind.\"[^3]\n- *Samaya*: Appears ~30× untranslated (e.g., \"protecting the *samaya* [*samaya*]\"; \"your *samaya* [*samaya*], O Vajrin\").[^4]\n- *Maṇḍala*: \"You must not teach about the sacred *vajra* [*bajra*], *ghaṇṭā*, and *mudrā* to a person who has not seen the *maṇḍala* [*maṇḍala*].\"[^5]\n\nAre they kept untranslated because they have no Old Javanese equivalent, or because the Sanskrit form carries authority the Javanese would dilute?\n\n[^1]: `unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/transliteration/#p-f5c28f`\n[^2]: `unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-906a8d`\n[^3]: `unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-906a8d`\n[^4]: `unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-1c4aa5`\n[^5]: `unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-4b996f`",
